Extremal Area Pedal and Antipedal Triangles

Mark Helman, Ronaldo Garcia, and Dan Reznik

Last update: 2020-07-13 09:12:27

1 Introduction

Given a reference triangle \(T={V_1}{V_2}{V_3}\) (shown blue below), its pedal triangle \(T'\) (red) with respect to a point \(P\) (called the pedal point) is defined by the feet of perpendiculars from \(P\) onto the sides of \(T\). Additionally, the antipedal triangle \(T''\) with respect to \(P\) (green) has sides through \(V_i\) perpendicular to \((V_i-P)\) (its vertices lie at the intersection of said sides) [1].

2 Sturms Theorem

In 1823, a then 20 year old Jacques Charles Franois Sturm (1803-1855), famously known for his SturmLiouville theory, proved the following remarkable fact [2]:

The isocurves of constant area of the pedal polygon \(T'\) are circles centered on the Circumcenter \(X_3\).

This is aptly illustrated in Figure 7.31, page 221 in [2], with \(O\) representing \(X_3\):

Sturm also showed that for each isocircle, the signed area \(A'\) of \(T'\) is given by:

\[ A'=\frac{A}{4}[1-(\frac{d}{R})^2] \]

Where \(A\) is the area of the reference \(T\), \(d\) is the radius of the isocircle, and \(R\) the circumradius, respectively. The formula implies that \(A'=A/4\) is maximal at \(d=0\), i.e., \(P=X_3\). So the extremal area pedal triangle is the pedal with respect to \(X_3\), i.e., the medial triangle, with vertices at the midpoint of the sides of \(T\).

Note that when \(d<R\) the area is positive (the vertices of both \(T\) and \(T'\) are ordered alike). At \(d=R\), \(P\) is on the circumcircle and \(T'\) degenerates to a zero-area triangle known as the Simson Line [1]. For \(d>R\), the vertices of the pedal are in reverse order with respect to \(T\) and its signed area becomes negative.

3 Steiners Curvature Centroid

A short 2 years later, eminent mathematician Jakob Steiner (1796-1863), only 6 years Sturms senior, generalized Sturms result to all polygons. He discovered that a special point \(K\) called the Curvature Centroid (der Krmmungs-Schwerpunkt) can be computed for any polygon with respect to which the pedal polygons has extremal area [3]. Let \(V_i,\theta_i\) denote an N-gon vertices and internal angles. \(K\) is given by:

\[ K = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^N{\sin(2\theta_i)V_i}}{\sum_{i=1}^N{\sin(2\theta_i)}} \]

Steiner proves the area will be maximal (resp. minimal) if \(\sum_i{sin(2\theta_i)}\) is positive (resp. negative). Notice that for parallelograms, the sum of double-angle sines is zero. Indeed, the area of pedal polygons to this shape is invariant over \(P\).

Corollary: the Centroid of Curvature for a triangle is \(X_3\), since its barycentrics are \(sin(2\theta_i)\), and this confirms Sturms result.

3.1 A potential misnomer: X(1115)

According to Mathworld [1], the triangle center with barycentrics \(\pi-\theta_i\) was named by Honsberger (1995) Steiners Curvature Centroid, listed as \(X_{1115}\) on ETC [4]. This could be confusing and/or erroneous. Steiners Curvature Centroid for a triangle is simply \(X_3\).

Note: as of July 10, 2020, Prof.Clark Kimberling has already changed \(X_{1115}\) to Exterior-Angle Curvature Centroid [4].

4 Minimal-Area Antipedal

The minimal-area antipedal must occur with respect to the Orthocenter \(X_4\) of the reference triangle. To see this, recall a theorem by Gallatly, page 58 [5]:

Let \(T\) be a triangle and \(T'\) its pedal with respect to a point \(P\). Let \(T^{*}\) be the antipedal of \(T\) with respect to \(P^*\), the isogonal conjugate of \(P\). Let \(A,A',A^{*}\) denote the areas of the three mentioned triangles. Then, \(A'A^{*}=A^2\).

To see this, recall \(X_4\) is the isogonal conjugate of \(X_3\). Suppose another point \(Y\) existed with respect to which an antipedal had area lower than \(A^*\). With \(A\) constant, this would imply a pedal with respect to \(Y^*\), the isogonal of \(Y\), of area higher than \(A'\), a contradiction since \(A'\) is maximal.

So the minimal antipedal is the anticomplementary triangle [1], whose area is \(4A\). As before, the antipedals maximal-area pedal polygon will be its medial, i.e., the original \(T\) itself.

Below non-linear isocurves of area for the antipedal triangle with respect to points in the plane is shownm. From left to right: an acute, right, and obtuse triangles are shown. The minimal-area antipedal (anticomplementary triangle) is shown green, as is this triangles \(X_3'\) (reference \(X_4\)). Note zero-area iso-curves along the circumcircle, where the antipedal triangle shrinks to a point.

5 Conclusion

We salute Sturm, Steiner, and Gallatly for these wonderful results!
